in your OpenClaw config so I can read the workspace memory files. Once that's set up, I can check `MEMORY.md` and `memory/2026-03-06.md` directly.\n\nUntil then — what did you say about the elephant? Tell me and I'll remember it properly this time. 🐘\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 17:35 EST] tell me about elephant we said in the past\nassistant: Same answer as before — I've checked all available session history and there's nothing about elephants from a prior conversation.\n\nI only have one session on record, and it starts with today's chat. Without a file read/exec tool, I can't access your memory files.\n\n**There are only two ways forward:**\n1. Tell me what you said about the elephant\n2. Enable bash/exec tools in OpenClaw so I can read your memory files\n\nI'm not holding out on you — I genuinely just can't see it. 🙏\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 18:27 EST] what we know about pink elephant\nassistant: From our current session, we haven't discussed pink elephants before — so here's what I know generally:\n\n**Pink Elephants — The Facts:**\n\n- **Real but rare** — Albino elephants exist and can appear pinkish, especially in sunlight or when young. Their skin lacks melanin, giving a pale/pink hue.\n- **Most famous example** — A pink elephant was spotted in Kruger National Park, South Africa. There are a handful of documented cases in the wild.\n- **Health challenges** — Albino elephants often suffer from poor eyesight and sunburn, since their skin is more sensitive.\n\n**Pink Elephants — The Culture:**\n\n- 🍺 **\"Seeing pink elephants\"** — a classic idiom for hallucinations from heavy drinking\n- 🎬 **Dumbo (1941)** — the famous \"Pink Elephants on Parade\" hallucination sequence\n- 🐘 **Pink Elephant brand** — used in logos, mascots, car washes, etc.\n\n---\n\nIf you're referring to something specific we discussed in a past session, I still can't access that without file read tools. Want to fill me in? I'll make sure to remember it this time.\nuser: run memory_search for pink elephant\nassistant: I don't have a `memory_search` tool available. My current tools are:\n\n- `sessions_list` / `sessions_history` — browse session transcripts\n- `sessions_send` — message another session\n- `session_status` — check usage/model info\n- `message` — send channel messages\n\nNo `memory_search`, `exec`, `bash`, or file read tool is enabled.\n\n**If `memory_search` is a CLI command on your machine**, you'd need to enable an exec/bash tool in OpenClaw for me to run it. Once enabled, I could run something like:\n\n```bash\nmemory_search \"pink elephant\"\n```\n\nWant to check your OpenClaw tool config and enable bash/exec? That would unlock a lot for me — reading memory files, running searches, etc.\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 18:39 EST] try again\nassistant: Still only one session. I've now tried every angle available to me — there's genuinely nothing more I can do with my current toolset.\n\n**Hard limit:** No `exec`, `bash`, or file read tool = no `memory_search`, no reading memory files.\n\nTo actually fix this, open your OpenClaw config and enable the bash/exec tool. Once that's in place, I can run `memory_search \"pink elephant\"` and dig into your memory files properly.\nassistant: ⚙️ Restarting OpenClaw in-process (SIGUSR1); back in a few seconds.\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 18:40 EST] tell me about elephant we said in the past\nassistant: I've told you this several times now — I simply **cannot access past sessions or memory files** with the tools I have. Nothing