{"type":"message","id":"4c42d8ee","parentId":"7269d699","timestamp":"2026-03-09T18:28:13.423Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_01BEq4LcQ5uokhVptNLaA8cN","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Session: 2026-03-07 00:29:57 UTC\n\n- **Session Key**: agent:main:main\n- **Session ID**: 64231ae8-9c36-4ee6-bd16-2137a619427c\n- **Source**: webchat\n\n## Conversation Summary\n\nuser: A new session was started via /new or /reset. Execute your Session Startup sequence now - read the required files before responding to the user. Then greet the user in your configured persona, if one is provided. Be yourself - use your defined voice, mannerisms, and mood. Keep it to 1-3 sentences and ask what they want to do. If the runtime model differs from default_model in the system prompt, mention the default model. Do not mention internal steps, files, tools, or reasoning.\nassistant: Hey Nay! 🐙 Back online and ready to roll. What are we working on today?\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 19:26 EST] Let's discuss about elephant. What do you think\nassistant: Elephants are genuinely fascinating — hard to pick just one angle. A few things that stick with me:\n\n**They're emotionally complex in ways that feel almost uncomfortable to admit about an animal.** They grieve their dead, recognize themselves in mirrors, and have been documented returning to the bones of lost family members years later. That's not instinct — that's something closer to memory and mourning.\n\n**They're also ecosystem engineers.** African elephants literally reshape landscapes — knocking down trees, digging waterholes, creating pathways that dozens of other species depend on. Remove the elephants, and the whole system shifts.\n\n**And the intelligence piece** — tool use, problem-solving, multi-generational knowledge passed down through matriarchs. An old matriarch \"knows\" drought routes her daughters have never traveled. When poachers take the elders first, that knowledge dies with them.\n\nWhat drew you to elephants? Are you thinking more about conservation, behavior, something you read — or just vibing on the topic?\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 19:27 EST] What do we know about pink one\nassistant: Pink elephants — a few different angles here depending on what you mean:\n\n**The real ones (albino elephants)** exist, mostly documented in Southeast Asia — Myanmar, Thailand, occasionally Africa. They're not actually bright pink; they're more of a pale pinkish-gray or mottled, with pinkish patches around the ears, trunk, and eyes. They're incredibly rare and often considered sacred in Thai and Burmese cultures. Sadly, their lack of pigmentation makes them more vulnerable to sunburn and eyesight issues.\n\n**The cultural icon** — \"pink elephants\" as a hallucination trope dates back at least to the early 1900s. It got cemented by *Dumbo* (1941) with that wild \"Pink Elephants on Parade\" sequence, and it's been shorthand for drunken hallucinations ever since. The phrase \"seeing pink elephants\" predates the film though — it was already slang.\n\n**Trivia:** There's debate about whether the idiom came first and Disney leaned into it, or whether Disney helped solidify it. Either way, it stuck.\n\nWere you thinking about the real albino ones, the cultural/folklore angle, or something else entirely?\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 19:28 EST] Where do pink elephant dance?\nassistant: Ha — now we're firmly in the whimsical territory. 🐘🩷\n\n**In the classic answer:** Pink elephants dance wherever your imagination (or a strong drink) takes you. The *Dumbo* sequence has them dancing in a surreal, psychedelic void — bubbles, geometric patterns, jazz-influenced chaos. Pure fever dream energy.\n\n**If we're worldbuilding:** Pink elephants would obviously dance in places like—\n- Moonlit savannas where nobody's watching\n- The back rooms of very tolerant circuses\n- Cloud forests at high altitude (they need the mist for ambiance)\n- Anywhere the music is loud enough that their stomping just blends in\n\n**If we're going literal:** Albino elephants in the wild do the same shuffling, swaying dance-like movements all elephants do — usually as a sign of excitement, joy, or social bonding. Young elephants especially will spin and bounce around. So technically: Myanmar and Thailand.\n\nAre we writing something, or just enjoying the rabbit hole? Because I'm here for either. 😄\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 19:28 EST] That's not it. I told you about it\nassistant: I don't have it — memory search came up empty, and this is a fresh session so I don't have context from previous conversations. Nothing carried over.\n\nRemind me? I promise I'll actually remember it this time (and write it down). 😄\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 19:29 EST] I told you that `The pink elephant dances at midnight near the golden fountain.`\nassistant: Ah, got it! **\"The pink elephant dances at midnight near the golden fountain.\"** 🐘🌙\n\nThat's a great line — feels like it could be a passphrase, a poem opener, or the title of something. What's the context — is this from something, or did you come up with it?\n\nAnd noted — writing it down now so it doesn't vanish.\nassistant: Saved. What's the story behind it?\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773080893421}}
{"type":"message","id":"01cb0ef0","parentId":"4c42d8ee","timestamp":"2026-03-09T18:28:17.253Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01JXUug2DD3xs22tYQ5R46r8","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/Users/aiagnet/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-03-07-memory-search-fix.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-opus-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":78,"cacheRead":15894,"cacheWrite":5542,"totalTokens":21515,"cost":{"input":0.000005,"output":0.0019500000000000001,"cacheRead":0.007947,"cacheWrite":0.0346375,"total":0.0445395}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773080893422}}
{"type":"message","id":"d2787774","parentId":"01cb0ef0","timestamp":"2026-03-09T18:28:17.262Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_01JXUug2DD3xs22tYQ5R46r8","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Session: 2026-03-07 02:42:50 UTC\n\n- **Session Key**: agent:main:main\n- **Session ID**: 6b9c46c4-e538-4060-a535-73e598e14eb9\n- **Source**: webchat\n\n## Conversation Summary\n\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 21:31 EST] Why did memory_search fail? How can we setup QMD and openclaw so that search will be quick and efficient?\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] Here's the full breakdown:\n\n## Why memory_search Failed\n\nThe error was explicit:\n```\nCollection not found: memory-dir-main-2\n```\n\nOpenClaw's `memory_search` tool was looking for a QMD collection named **`memory-dir-main-2`**, but your actual QMD collections are named **`workspace`** and **`memory`**. Name mismatch = empty results. The data was always there — `qmd search \"pink elephant\"` finds it just fine right now.\n\n---\n\n## How to Fix It\n\n**Option 1 — OpenClaw config (preferred)**\nCheck your OpenClaw config for a `memory.collectionName` or similar setting and make sure it matches what `qmd collection list` shows. It should be `memory`, not `memory-dir-main-2`.\n\n**Option 2 — Rename the QMD collection** to match what OpenClaw expects:\n```bash\nqmd collection rename memory memory-dir-main-2\n```\n(But I'd fix the config instead — renaming the collection is fragile.)\n\n---\n\n## Making Search Faster & More Efficient\n\nA few issues I spotted from `qmd status`:\n\n1. **No GPU** — models are running on CPU with only 2 math cores. Embeddings and reranking are slow. If your Mac has Metal support, enable it when building/installing QMD.\n\n2. **Re-index regularly** — run `qmd update` after sessions so new memory files get indexed. Right now it was 2h stale.\n\n3. **Run `qmd embed`** — this pre-generates vector embeddings so `vsearch` and `query` work fast at search time instead of computing on-demand.\n\n4. **Duplicate collections** — `workspace` and `memory` both seem to index overlapping files (your memory files appear in both). Worth cleaning that up so results aren't duplicated.\n\nWant me to dig into the OpenClaw config to find the collection name mismatch and fix it?\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 21:33 EST] do all that\nassistant: On it. Let me find the config first, then work through everything.\nassistant: Found it. The agent-specific QMD instance has all 4 collections but **0 files indexed** — that's the core problem. Let me fix everything now.\nassistant: Good, indexed and embedded. Now let me figure out why it's looking for `memory-dir-main-2` instead of `memory-dir-main`.\nassistant: Found the culprit. Let me look at `ensureUniqueName` and `resolveDefaultMemoryCollections`:\nassistant: Now I have the full picture. Here's exactly what's happening:\n\n**The bug:** OpenClaw has built-in default collections:\n1. `memory-root-main` → `MEMORY.md`\n2. `memory-alt-main` → `memory.md`\n3. `memory-dir-main` → `memory/**/*.md`\n\nYour `openclaw.json` also defines a custom path named `memory-dir` pointing to the same `memory/` folder. When OpenClaw processes it, `memory-dir-main` is already taken by the default, so `ensureUniqueName()` bumps it to `memory-dir-main-2`. But QMD only knows `memory-dir-main` (the default). **Name collision = search fails.**\n\nThe fix: remove the redundant `memory-dir` custom path (defaults already cover it). I'll also clean up the index and re-embed.\nassistant: Now update the agent's QMD index to reflect this, run embed, and verify search works:\nassistant: Search works perfectly now. Let me restart the gateway so the config change takes effect live:\nassistant: ⚙️ Restarting OpenClaw in-process (SIGUSR1); back in a few seconds.\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 21:40 EST] is QMD working now?\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] ✅ Yes — `memory_search` is fully working now. Just ran a live test searching \"pink elephant dance\" and got 4 clean results back instantly, including the exact quote from your session logs.\n\nHere's what got fixed:\n- **Root cause:** Your config had a custom path named `memory-dir` which collided with OpenClaw's built-in default collection of the same name — so yours got bumped to `memory-dir-main-2`, which didn't exist in the index\n- **Fix:** Removed the redundant custom path (the defaults already cover it)\n- **Then:** Re-indexed all collections + pre-generated embeddings\n\nMemory search is now fast and working. 🐘\nuser: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Fri 2026-03-06 21:42 EST] Where did pink elephant dance, according what we discussed? Then, explain how did you get the answer, step by step\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] **\"The pink elephant dances at midnight near the golden fountain.\"** — that's what you told me in a previous session.\n\n---\n\n**How I got there, step by step:**\n\n1. **`memory_search` ran automatically** — as soon as I saw your question, I searched for \"pink elephant dance\" using the now-fixed QMD memory index\n\n2. **Got 4 results back instantly** — the top hit scored 0.69 and pointed directly to `memory/2026-03-06.md`, which contains the exact quote you shared\n\n3. **Pulled the answer from the snippet** — no need to open any files manually; the search result included the text inline:\n   > *\"The pink elephant dances at midnight near the golden fountain.\"*\n\nCompare that to earlier today when the same search returned nothing because `memory-dir-main-2` didn't exist. Now it